- The original code had `if (shift == 0)` which would write a completed byte when `shift` became 0 (after processing the 7th bit in a byte)
- This caused the 8th bit of each byte to be lost and not written properly
- When there was an incomplete final byte, the condition `if (length > 0 && shift > 0)` would only write it if `shift` was still positive, but after processing 8 bits, `shift` would be -1, so the final byte wouldn't be written

### The Fix
I changed the code from:
```java
if (shift == 0) {
    header.write(cache);
    shift = 7;
    cache = 0;
}
// ...
if (length > 0 && shift > 0) {
    header.write(cache);
}
```

To:
```java
if (shift < 0) {
    header.write(cache);
    shift = 7;
    cache = 0;
}
// ...
if (length > 0 && shift < 7) {
    header.write(cache);
}
```

### Validation
- The triggering test `org.apache.commons.compress.archivers.sevenz.SevenZOutputFileTest::testSevenEmptyFiles` now passes
- Related tests like `testSixEmptyFiles`, `testEightEmptyFiles`, and `testSixFilesSomeNotEmpty` also pass
- The fix ensures that all bits are properly written to the 7z file header, including the final incomplete byte when needed

The patch is saved in `blind_fix.patch` as requested.

